Perry's financial position was stable 
enough for him to contemplate matrimony,
 and on 23 August 1798 he married Anne Hull 
(1773–1815), ‘a woman of pleasing manners and 
intelligent countenance’ (Holcroft, 2.180);
 they had eight children, including Sir 
Thomas Erskine Perry and Anne Horatia (d. 1855),
 who married the diplomatist John Crawfurd 
(1783–1868). Anne Perry died in February 
1815 after having resided for some time 
at Lisbon to recover from consumption, 
only to be carried off by pirates on 
her voyage back to England and kept prisoner 
in Africa for several weeks. She died at 
Bordeaux after her release and on her way home. 
Perry had saved her life on 26 December 1798 
when her clothes caught fire; he put out the 
flames with his hands, burning them badly. 
